Description . Stolon creeping on alga, adherent surface flattened ( fig. 3 H) diameter ca . 125 µm; stolon mostly linear and smooth, occasionally tortuous and branched. Colony ca . 2.5 cm high ( fig. 3 G); growth habit arborescent, in one plane, with sparingly branched stems. Stems straight, monosiphonic, with 1–3 basal constrictions above stolon (
fig. 3I
). Auto-epizoism quite frequent, with 1–3 stolonal tubes running over basal part of primary stem, giving rise occasionally to secondary stems whose axes are (nearly) perpendicular to those of main stem. Perisarc moderately thick and pale horn basally, thinning out and becoming transparent distally. Stems divided into internodes by means of distinct oblique nodes, alternately sloping left and right ( fig. 3 N); internodes with a distal apophysis supporting primary hydrophores, basally with a bulge above node. Internodes relatively long (455–560 µm), straight, collinear, though imperceptibly geniculate distally; diameter at node 80–110 µm. Primary hydrophores alternate, free from stem, generally very long (205–465 µm), perisarc wrinkled above base towards middle part ( fig. 3 O), articulated; occasionally, distalmost internodes with much shorter (95–140 µm), smooth primary hydrophores ( fig. 3 O, lower left). Pseudodiaphragm variably present on adcauline side of hydrophores, from slightly marked to obvious, and reaching abcauline side. Branches in the same plane as main stem (colony coplanar), arising irregularly from primary and secondary hydrophores ( fig. 3 K–M); colonies with up to 2nd order branches; branches with same structure and shape as stem. Hydrotheca rather deep (55–70 µm), margin widely flaring and much everted, diameter 110–125 µm at base, 160–200 µm at rim; wall slightly asymmetrical, adaxial side tilted towards internode; desmocytes numerous, visible as refringent nodules above diaphragm. Secondary and tertiary hydrophores common and of variable length, arising from diaphragm of primary hydrothecae; pseudodiaphragm slightly marked or absent. Hydranths absent, the cnidome could not be examined. Inspected colony with mature, female gonothecae. The latter borne abundantly on stolonal tubes, along basal parts of stems ( fig. 4 B), or arising from internode apophyses in replacement of a hydrotheca ( fig. 4A ); exceptionally, gonothecae arising from middle part of primary hydrophores ( fig. 3 P). Gonotheca almost oval in frontal view ( fig. 4 C–D), laterally flattened ( fig. 4 E), borne on smooth pedicel of variable length; 800–1000 µm long, 685– 765 µm wide in frontal view; perisarc smooth to undulate, relatively thick; aperture a shallow, circular (diameter 160–200 µm), apical depression, surrounded by thickened perisarc ( fig. 4 C). Sporosac oval, not occupying the whole lumen of gonotheca, delimited by thin perisarc layer, containing 6–10 oval eggs, each ca . 175 × 130 µm.

Remarks . The present material is mainly characterized by its very peculiar coplanar colony, with straight stems and branches, and much long, articulated hydrophores. Similar specimens, possessing collinear internodes, were found by Hartlaub (1905) (as
H. flexile Allman, 1888
) in material from Punta Arenas, Chile . Long primary hydrophores were mentioned and/or figured by both Hartlaub (1905) (p. 613, fig. K3a) and Ralph (1958) (p. 335, fig. 11L). They were thought to belong to aberrant colonies, as stated by Vervoort & Watson (2003). Until more material is examined, it is difficult to say if these long hydrophores appear after mechanical breakage and a subsequent regeneration step.
